cipline but as a worldly art of grappling with issues of daily and urgent human significance. In this classic work, Martha Nussbaum maintains that these Hellenistic schools have been unjustly neglected in recent philosophic accounts of what the classical "tradition" has to offer. By examining texts of philosophers such as Epicurus, Lucretius, and Seneca, she recovers a valuable source for current moral and political thought and encourages us to reconsider philosophical argument as a technique through which to improve lives. Written for general readers and specialists, The Therapy of Desire addresses compelling issues ranging from the psychology of human passion through rhetoric to the role of philosophy in public and private life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAggression.  aAmbiguity.  aAnalogy.  aAnger.  aAristotelian ethics.  aAristotelianism.  aAristotle.  aAtaraxia.  aAwareness.  aCareer.  aCausality.  aChrysippus.  aContingency (philosophy).  aCriticism.  aCritique.  aCruelty.  aDe Ira.  aDe rerum natura.  aDeath anxiety (psychology).  aDeed.  aDemocritus.  aDialectic.  aDisease.  aDisgust.  aDisposition.  aEpictetus.  aEpicureanism.  aEpicurus.  aEroticism.  aEthics.  aEudaimonia.  aExplanation.  aFalsity.  aFeeling.  aForm of life (philosophy).  aGenerosity.  aGrief.  aHatred.  aHedonism.  aHostility.  aImagery.  aIndication (medicine).  aInjunction.  aInquiry.  aLecture.  aLibido.  aLiterature.  aLucretius.  aMorality.  aMotivation.  aMutilation.  aNarrative.  aNicomachean Ethics.  aObstacle.  aOptimism.  aPathos.  aPhaedrus (dialogue).  aPhenomenon.  aPhilodemus.  aPhilosopher.  aPhilosophy.  aPhronesis.  aPity.  aPlato